You can use bitwise operators.
```java
public class ColorBytes {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		int a = 23, r = 121, g = 255, b = 130, color = 0;
		// pack four components into one int color
		color = a;
		color &lt;&lt;= 8;
		color += r;
		color &lt;&lt;= 8;
		color += g;
		color &lt;&lt;= 8;
		color += b;
		//
		System.out.println(&quot;a, r, g, b = &quot; + a + &quot;, &quot; + r + &quot;, &quot; + g + &quot;, &quot; + b);
		System.out.println(&quot;color = &quot; + color);
		a = r = g = b = 0;
		// unpack color to get its four
		// components back in a, r, g, b
		b = color &amp; 0xFF;
		g = (color &gt;&gt; 8) &amp; 0xFF;
		r = (color &gt;&gt; 16) &amp; 0xFF;
		a = (color &gt;&gt; 24) &amp; 0xFF;
		//
		System.out.println(&quot;a, r, g, b = &quot; + a + &quot;, &quot; + r + &quot;, &quot; + g + &quot;, &quot; + b);
	}
}
```
To pack `color` we do the following.
1. We add the value of `a` to `color`.
2. We shift the value of `color` 8 bits to the left.
3. We add the value of `r` to `color`.
4. We shift the new value of `color` 8 bits to the left.
5. We add the value of `g` to `color`.
6. We shift the new value of `color` 8 bits to the left.
7. Finally, we add the value of `b` to `color`.

To unpack `color` we do the following.
1. Mask out the last 8 bits of `color` to get the value of `b`.
2. Shift the value of `color` 8 bits to the right and mask out the last 8 bits of the new value of `color` to get the value of `g`.
3. Shift the value of `color` 16 bits to the right and mask out the last 8 bits to get the value of `r`.
4. Shift the value of `color` 24 bits to the right and mask out the last 8 bits to get the value of `a`.

Refer to [Bitwise and Bit Shift Operators](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/op3.html) in Oracle&#39;s Java tutorials.

